<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-707-562  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 707 562.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 6 1990 v7 n31 p12(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Pair of utilities aim to aid ToolBook development. (HeizerSoftware's ConvertIt! and Asymetrix Corp.'s ToolBook Author'sResource Kit utility programs) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Heizer Software Inc. (product introduction)Asymetrix Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   ConvertIt! (Data conversion software) (product introduction)Toolbook Author's Resource Kit (Program development software)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionUtility ProgramsData Conversionm Program Development Tools.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Two new utilities are set to appear to help software developers bolster theirapplications arsenal for ToolBook, Asymetrix Corp.'s end-user developmentenvironment for Windows 3.0.andM;Heizer Software last week shipped ConvertIt!, a utility that transformsMacintosh HyperCard stacks into the ToolBook file format, letting developersmove HyperCard applications to the Windows 3.0 environment.andM;Separately, Asymetrix announced plans to ship next week the ToolBook Author'sResource Kit (ARK), which will include a royalty-free, run-time version ofToolBook and three Windows 3.0 dynamic link libraries (DLLs).andM;One of Asymetrix's three new DLLs will let ToolBook applications accessprograms written in C or other Windows-compatible languages, including dBASEIII data files.andP;  The second DLL will let users copy, delete and perform otherMS-DOS functions within a ToolBook application instead of returning to theWindows shell.andP;  The third will configure ToolBook applications to work withdisplay devices, printers and fonts, said Shelly Julien, Asymetrix manager ofdeveloper relations in Bellevue, Wash.andM;Asymetrix is including a run-time version of ToolBook in the $450 ARK toallow developers to distribute multiple copies of their ToolBook applicationswithout extra costs, Julien said.andP;  Microsoft Corp. currently bundles theToolBook run-time version with Windows 3.0, &quot;but our arrangement withMicrosoft is not indefinite,&quot; she said.andM;Heizer Software's ConvertIt!, available now for $199, has two maincomponents: an export utility that translates HyperCard stacks into a fileformat called Hypermedia Interchange File Format (HIFF) and an import utilitythat lets ToolBook read an HIFF file so it can be edited and transformed intoa ToolBook application, said Ray Heizer, president of the Pleasant Hill,Calif., firm.andM;&quot;It converts about 80 percent of the file on average,&quot; Heizer said.andO;ConvertIt! flags scripts that have not been fully translated so developerscan change the HyperTalk commands and functions into their ToolBookequivalent.andP;  Heizer Software has converted more than 350 of its HyperCardapplications over to ToolBook using the utility, he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>